display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma _g\colon  X'\to  X\times _Y X]]></fr:tex> is an open immersion.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>Indeed, this is the inverse image of the diagonal morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X\to  X\times _Y X]]></fr:tex> by
  <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[g\times _Y \mathrm {id}_{X'}\colon  X'\times _Y X\to  X\times _Y X.]]></fr:tex>
  One can also introduce the annihilator ideal <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {d}_{X/Y}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _{X/Y}^1]]></fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>different ideal</fr:em> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X/Y]]></fr:tex>;
  it defines a closed sub-prescheme of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> which, set-theoretically, is the set of point where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X/Y]]></fr:tex> is ramified, i.e. not unramified.</fr:p><fr:tree
